{"title_page": "Lake Grahovo", "text_new": "{{short description|Lake in Montenegro}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Lake Grahovo\n| image = Grahovsko jezero.jpg\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Grahovo, Nik\u0161i\u0107|Grahovo]]\n| coords =  {{coord|42|40|15|N|18|37|48|E|type:waterbody_region:ME|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = [[Montenegro]]\n| length = {{convert|700|m}}\n| width = {{convert|200|m}}\n| area = \n| depth = \n| max-depth = {{convert|25|m}}\n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|788|m}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n'''Lake Grahovo''' ([[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]]: Grahovsko jezero, \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e \u0458\u0435\u0437\u0435\u0440\u043e) is a [[lake]] in [[Nik\u0161i\u0107]] municipality, near the town of [[Grahovo, Nik\u0161i\u0107|Grahovo]] in southwestern [[Montenegro]].\n\nIt is an artificial lake which is an accumulation of the Grahovo River. Bottom of the lake is mostly [[dolomite (rock)|dolomite]]-based. The lake itself is 700 meters long, 200 meters wide and 25 meters deep.<ref>[http://niksic.travel/?page_id=15 Turisti\u010dka organizacija Nik\u0161i\u0107 - atrakcije]</ref> The dam is 30 metres high, and three meters wide. The lake is a significant water reservoir used for the agricultural production of [[Grahovo, Nik\u0161i\u0107|Grahovo]], but is also used for sport and recreation.<ref>[http://www.dinarskogorje.com/grahovo.html Grahovo - Dinarsko gorje]</ref> Construction of the dam was initiated in 1952, finished in 1962, while it has undergone a reconstruction in 1988.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Grahovo (Nik\u0161i\u0107)]]\n*[[Grahovac]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lakes of Montenegro|Grahovo]]\n[[Category:Nik\u0161i\u0107 Municipality]]\n\n{{Montenegro-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Lake in Montenegro}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Lake Grahovo\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Grahovo, Nik\u0161i\u0107|Grahovo]]\n| coords =  {{coord|42|40|15|N|18|37|48|E|type:waterbody_region:ME|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = [[Montenegro]]\n| length = {{convert|700|m}}\n| width = {{convert|200|m}}\n| area = \n| depth = \n| max-depth = {{convert|25|m}}\n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|788|m}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n'''Lake Grahovo''' ([[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]]: Grahovsko jezero, \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e \u0458\u0435\u0437\u0435\u0440\u043e) is a [[lake]] in [[Nik\u0161i\u0107]] municipality, near the town of [[Grahovo, Nik\u0161i\u0107|Grahovo]] in southwestern [[Montenegro]].\n\nIt is an artificial lake which is an accumulation of the Grahovo River. Bottom of the lake is mostly [[dolomite (rock)|dolomite]]-based. The lake itself is 700 meters long, 200 meters wide and 25 meters deep.<ref>[http://niksic.travel/?page_id=15 Turisti\u010dka organizacija Nik\u0161i\u0107 - atrakcije]</ref> The dam is 30 metres high, and three meters wide. The lake is a significant water reservoir used for the agricultural production of [[Grahovo, Nik\u0161i\u0107|Grahovo]], but is also used for sport and recreation.<ref>[http://www.dinarskogorje.com/grahovo.html Grahovo - Dinarsko gorje]</ref> Construction of the dam was initiated in 1952, finished in 1962, while it has undergone a reconstruction in 1988.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Grahovo (Nik\u0161i\u0107)]]\n*[[Grahovac]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lakes of Montenegro|Grahovo]]\n[[Category:Nik\u0161i\u0107 Municipality]]\n\n{{Montenegro-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Smooth O", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Grahovo"}
{"title_page": "Queenston, St. Catharines", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Queenston\n|settlement_type          = Neighbourhood\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[Canada]]\n|subdivision_type1        = Province\n|subdivision_type2        = Region\n|subdivision_type3        = City\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Ontario]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Regional Municipality of Niagara|Niagara]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[St. Catharines]]\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|area_total_km2           = 7.11\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_total         = 11326\n|population_as_of         = 2016\n|population_footnotes     = [https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/en/geo]\n|population_density_km2   = 1593\n\n}}\n\n'''Queenston''' is a neighbourhood in the city of [[St. Catharines]], [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rayburn|first1=Alan|title=Place names of Ontario|date=1997|publisher=University of Toronto Press|location=Toronto|isbn=9780802072078|p=284}}</ref> \n\nThe community is bordered on the west by [[Niagara Regional Road 46]], on the east by the [[Welland Canal]], on the north by the [[QEW]] and Welland Avenue, and on the south by the [[Ontario Highway 406|406]], Lincoln Avenue and [[Niagara Regional Road 81]].<ref>Ontario Early Years Niagara Region (2006). [http://www.uey.eccdc.org/development/stcatharines.php \"St. Catharines\"]</ref>\nThe west side of this neighbourhood is composed of employments lands, while the east side is composed of medium to high density residential and mixed use properties.<ref>City of St. Catharines. [https://www.stcatharines.ca/en/buildin/resources/Comprehensive-Zoning-By-law-No.-2013-283.pdf \"City of St. Catharines Zoning By\u2013Law\"], p. 234-235, 16 December 2013</ref>\n\nNotable locations in this neighbourhood include:\n* [[British Methodist Episcopal Church, Salem Chapel]]\n* [[Garden City Skyway]]\n* [[Homer Bridge]]\n* the lands of the former [[St. Catharines General Hospital]].\n\nParks:<ref>St. Catharines. [https://www.stcatharines.ca/en/facilities/Index.aspx \"Parks, Playing Fields, Courts & Green Spaces\"]</ref>\n* Barley Drive Park\n* Bartlett Park\n* Canal Valley\n* Centennial Gardens\n* Douglas Park\n* Fitzgerald Park\n* Kernahan Park\n* Plymouth Avenue Park\n* Princess Park\n\nPublic Schools:<ref>District School Board of Niagara (2019). [https://drive.google.com/open?id=1H80B3H3EIOZSrql5014WOBbA42M&usp=sharing \"DSBN Schools & Centres\"]</ref>\n* Connaught Public School\n* Jeanne Sauv\u00e9 French Immersion Public School\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Center=Queenston\n|East=[[Niagara-on-the-Lake]]\n|North=[[Facer, St. Catharines|Facer]]\n|Northeast=[[Carlton - Bunting, St. Catharines|Carlton - Bunting]]\n|Northwest=[[Fairview, St. Catharines|Fairview]]\n|South=[[Glenridge, St. Catharines|Glenridge]]\n|Southeast=[[Merritton, St. Catharines|Merritton]]\n|Southwest=[[Downtown St. Catharines|Downtown]]\n|West=[[Haig, St. Catharines|The Haig]]\n}}\n{{Communities in St. Catharines, Ontario}}\n\n{{coord missing|Ontario}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in St. Catharines]]\n\n{{Ontario-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Queenston\n|settlement_type          = Neighbourhood\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[Canada]]\n|subdivision_type1        = Province\n|subdivision_type2        = Region\n|subdivision_type3        = City\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Ontario]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Regional Municipality of Niagara|Niagara]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[St. Catharines]]\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|area_total_km2           = 7.11\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_total         = 11326\n|population_as_of         = 2016\n|population_footnotes     = [https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/en/geo]\n|population_density_km2   = 1593\n\n}}\n\n'''Queenston''' is a neighbourhood in the city of [[St. Catharines]], [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rayburn|first1=Alan|title=Place names of Ontario|date=1997|publisher=University of Toronto Press|location=Toronto|isbn=9780802072078|p=284}}</ref> \n\nThe community is bordered on the west by [[Niagara Regional Road 46]], on the east by the [[Welland Canal]], on the north by the [[QEW]] and Welland Avenue, and on the south by the [[Ontario Highway 406|406]], Lincoln Avenue and [[Niagara Regional Road 81]].<ref>Ontario Early Years Niagara Region (2006). [http://www.uey.eccdc.org/development/stcatharines.php \"St. Catharines\"]</ref>\nThe west side of this neighbourhood is composed of employments lands, while the east side is composed of medium to high density residential and mixed use properties.<ref>City of St. Catharines. [https://www.stcatharines.ca/en/buildin/resources/Comprehensive-Zoning-By-law-No.-2013-283.pdf \"City of St. Catharines Zoning By\u2013Law\"], p. 234-235, 16 December 2013</ref>\n\nNotable locations in this neighbourhood include:\n* [[British Methodist Episcopal Church, Salem Chapel]]\n* [[Garden City Skyway]]\n* [[Homer Bridge]]\n* the lands of the former [[St. Catharines General Hospital]].\n\nParks:<ref>St. Catharines. [https://www.stcatharines.ca/en/facilities/Index.aspx \"Parks, Playing Fields, Courts & Green Spaces\"]</ref>\n* Barley Drive Park\n* Bartlett Park\n* Canal Valley\n* Centenial Gardens\n* Douglas Park\n* Fitzgerald Park\n* Kernahan Park\n* Plymouth Avenue Park\n* Princess Park\n\nPublic Schools:<ref>District School Board of Niagara (2019). [https://drive.google.com/open?id=1H80B3H3EIOZSrql5014WOBbA42M&usp=sharing \"DSBN Schools & Centres\"]</ref>\n* Connaught Public School\n* Jeanne Sauv\u00e9 French Immersion Public School\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Center=Queenston\n|East=[[Niagara-on-the-Lake]]\n|North=[[Facer, St. Catharines|Facer]]\n|Northeast=[[Carlton - Bunting, St. Catharines|Carlton - Bunting]]\n|Northwest=[[Fairview, St. Catharines|Fairview]]\n|South=[[Glenridge, St. Catharines|Glenridge]]\n|Southeast=[[Merritton, St. Catharines|Merritton]]\n|Southwest=[[Downtown St. Catharines|Downtown]]\n|West=[[Haig, St. Catharines|The Haig]]\n}}\n{{Communities in St. Catharines, Ontario}}\n\n{{coord missing|Ontario}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in St. Catharines]]\n\n{{Ontario-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queenston,_St._Catharines"}
{"title_page": "2002 Irish Masters", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox Individual Snooker Tournament\n|tournament_name=Irish Masters\n|dates=19\u201324 March 2002\n|venue=Citywest Hotel\n|location=[[Saggart]], [[Dublin]]\n|country=Republic of Ireland\n|organisation=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]\n|format=Non-[[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]] event\n|Total prize fund=\u20ac251,000\n|winners_share=\u20ac100,000\n|highest_break={{flagathlete|[[John Higgins]]|SCO}} (140)\n|winner={{flagathlete|[[John Higgins]]|SCO}}\n|runner_up={{flagathlete|[[Peter Ebdon]]|ENG}}\n|score=10\u20133\n|previous=[[2001 Irish Masters|2001]]\n|next=[[2003 Irish Masters|2003]]\n}}\nThe '''2002 Irish Masters''' (known as the '''2002 Citywest Irish Masters''' for sponsorship reasons) was a professional invitational [[snooker]] tournament which was held at the Citywest Hotel in [[Saggart]], [[Dublin]], from 19&nbsp;to 24&nbsp;March. It was the 25th edition of the [[Irish Masters]] and the fourth and final [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA) invitational event of the [[2001\u201302 snooker season|2001\u201302 season]]. The tournament was co-sponsored by the Citywest hotel group and the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Department of Health and Children]] and broadcast by [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]. The competition followed the season's third invitational event, the [[2002 Masters (snooker)|2002 Masters]].\n\n[[John Higgins]], the world number three, won the competition, defeating the world number seven [[Peter Ebdon]] ten {{cuegloss|frame|frames}} to three (10\u20133) in the final. It was Higgins' second Irish Masters victory, his fourth in a tournament that season and the 24th of his career. In the semi-finals Higgins defeated [[Matthew Stevens]] 6\u20135 and Ebdon won 6\u20133 over [[Ken Doherty]]. Higgins produced the tournament's highest {{cuegloss|break}} of 140 in the eighth frame of his semi-final match against Stevens to earn \u20ac5,000 and a further \u20ac100,000 for winning the event. \n\n==Background==\nFounded in 1978 by the [[Benson & Hedges]] tobacco company as the [[Republic of Ireland]]'s major snooker event, the [[Irish Masters]] originated as a snooker [[Exhibition game|challenge match]] and became an elimination tournament.<ref name=\"Irish Masters\">{{cite web|last=Turner|first=Chris|title=Irish Masters|url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/irishmast.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216155735/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/irishmast.html|archivedate=16 February 2012|publisher=Chris Turner's Snooker Archive|accessdate=18 November 2010}}</ref> The 2002 competition was the 25th edition of the competition,<ref name=\"Preview\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/o-sullivan-leads-star-cast-1.1050966|title=O'Sullivan leads star cast|date=19 February 2002|work=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=19 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419190852/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/o-sullivan-leads-star-cast-1.1050966|archive-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> and the fourth and final [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA) invitational event of the [[2001\u201302 snooker season|2001\u201302 season]].<ref name=\"SOrgEntry\" /> It featured a 12-player main draw held at the Citywest Hotel in [[Saggart]], [[Dublin]], from&nbsp;19 to 24&nbsp;March,<ref name=\"Irish Masters\" /><ref name=SOrgEntry>{{cite web|title=Citywest Irish Masters 2002|url=http://www.snooker.org/Trn/0102/im2002_res.shtml|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=15 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020205531/http://www.snooker.org/TRN/0102/im2002_res.shtml|archive-date=20 October 2019}}</ref> and was co-sponsored by the hotel group [[Citywest]] and the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Department of Health and Children]].<ref name=\"Irish Masters\" /><ref name=\"Preview\">{{cite web|title=Ronnie Aims For Irish Repeat|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=688&category=56|publisher=World Snooker|date=19 March 2002|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021223144539/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=688&category=56|archivedate=23 December 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> It had a prize fund of \u20ac251,000,<ref name=\"PrizeMoney\">{{cite web|title=Prize Money Breakdown|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/money.asp|publisher=World Snooker|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020820192644/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/money.asp|archivedate=20 August 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the host broadcaster was [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA total of 12 players competed in the Irish Masters: the top eleven players in the [[Snooker world rankings 2001/2002|world rankings]],<ref name=\"Preview\" /> and a [[Wild card (sports)|wild card]] entry, the world number sixteen, [[Fergal O'Brien]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Murray|first=Shane|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0218/162198-snooker/|title=Irish Masters details announced|date=18 February 2002|access-date=15 February 2002|url-status=live|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215203250/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0218/162198-snooker/|archive-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Each of the 12 players were [[Seed (sports)|seeded]], with the first seed being [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]], the 2001 Irish Masters winner, and the reigning [[2001 UK Championship|UK]] and [[2001 World Snooker Championship|world champion]].<ref name=\"Preview\" /> [[Steve Davis]], the eight-time Irish Masters winner, missed the event for the first time since the [[1986 Irish Masters|1986 tournament]] because he fell to 21st in the world rankings and was not given a wild card.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A83999386/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=364d71aa|title=No place for Davis at the top table; Snooker|date=19 March 2002|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=43|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The number of maximum {{cuegloss|frame|frames}} played in a match increased from 11 in the first round, the quarter-finals and the semi-finals to the best-of-19 frames final on 24 March.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\">{{cite web|title=Citywest Irish Masters 2002|url=http://www.worldofsnooker.co.uk/invitational/irishmasters02.htm|publisher=World of Snooker|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020623132850/http://www.worldofsnooker.co.uk/invitational/irishmasters02.htm|archivedate=23 June 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Prize money===\nThe breakdown of prize money for the 2002 tournament is listed below.<ref name=\"PrizeMoney\" />\n{{col-begin}}\n* Winner: \u20ac100,000\n* Runner-up:  \u20ac38,000\n* Semi-final (\u00d72): \u20ac19,000\n* Quarter-final (\u00d74): \u20ac10,000\n* First-round (\u00d74):  \u20ac7,500\n* Highest break (\u00d71): \u20ac5,000\n* Total:  \u20ac251,000\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Tournament summary==\n===Round 1===\nThe first round of the tournament was held from 19&nbsp;to 20&nbsp;March as best-of-11 frame matches.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=110Schedule>{{cite web|title=Citywest Irish Masters|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/utils/displaypage.php?page=/snooker/cont/trn/sched/irishmastersoop02.php|publisher=110Sport|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020421090902/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/utils/displaypage.php?page=%2Fsnooker%2Fcont%2Ftrn%2Fsched%2Firishmastersoop02.php|archivedate=21 April 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> World number eight [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] defeated the reigning Masters champion [[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]] 6\u20134 in their third meeting of the season.<ref name=LeeHunter110>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05301.php|title=Lee Foxes Hunter To End Dublin Drought|last=Hendon|first=David|date=19 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030523042858/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05301.php|archive-date=23 May 2003|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=LeeHunterIndy>{{Cite news|last=Francis|first=Allen|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84008154/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=413d3d68|title=Snooker: Lee to face familiar foe|date=20 March 2002|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=25|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The match was equalled at 3\u20133 and then 4\u20134 before Lee compiled {{Cuegloss|break|breaks}} of 72 and 88 to go through to the quarter-finals.<ref name=LeeHunterIndy/> Lee said he had worked to improve his technique and was pleased with it.<ref name=LeeHunter110/> World number seven [[Peter Ebdon]] won 6\u20132 against world championship semi-finalist [[Joe Swail]]. Ebdon compiled breaks of 120 and 81 to move clear of Swail and win the match\u2014this after Swail had missed a {{Cuegloss|red ball}} that would have allowed him to win the fifth frame. Both players agreed that Swail's error was the game's turning point.<ref name=WSSwailRed>{{Cite web|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=772&category=56|title=Crucial Miss Puts Swail In The Red|date=20 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020406093822/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=772&category=56|archive-date=6 April 2002|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Matthew Stevens]] won 6\u20135 over [[Jimmy White]], who made his 20th successive appearance in the Irish Masters.<ref name=BBCDay2>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/1884361.stm|title=Stevens and Hendry cruise|date=20 March 2002|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215203301/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/1884361.stm|archive-date=15 February 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Ahead 3\u20131, Stevens fell 4\u20133 behind White at the mid-session interval after he produced breaks of 106 and 102 and a {{Cuegloss|clearance}} of 65 to the {{Cuegloss|black ball}}.<ref name=StevensWhite110>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05306.php|title=Today Defeat, Tomorrow The World For Jimmy|last=Hendon|first=David|date=20 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020421054955/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05306.php|archive-date=15 April 2002|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> White missed a red to win the match while on a break of 62 and Stevens made a 58 clearance to the {{Cuegloss|pink ball}}. Stevens missed the black and White {{Cuegloss|pot|potted}} it to force a final frame,<ref name=StevensWhite110/> which Stevens won 75\u201314.<ref name=BBCDay2/> [[Stephen Hendry]], the seven-time world champion, took a 6\u20132 victory over O'Brien. Leading 2\u20131 with a break of 74, O'Brien was tied when Hendry produced a 112 break. Hendry then made breaks of 98 and 100 en route to his win as O'Brien accumulated 41 points in that time.<ref name=HendryHerald>{{Cite news|last=Price|first=Gerald|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84045249/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=63aa481c|title=Hendry's centuries are enough|date=21 March 2002|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=34|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Quarter-finals===\nThe four best-of-11 frame quarter-finals took place from 21&nbsp;to 22&nbsp;March with the first-round winners playing one of the top four seeds.<ref name=\"Irish Masters\" /><ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=\"110Schedule\" /> Ebdon was the first player through to the semi-finals when he defeated world number one [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 6\u20134. He took a 5\u20132 lead from breaks of 110, 77 and 113 along with a 93 clearance. Williams then reduced the deficit to 5\u20134 before he missed the black in the tenth frame and Ebdon won the match.<ref name=RTEEbdon>{{Cite news|last=Murray|first=Shane|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0321/162944-snooker/|title=Ebdon secures possible semi clash with Doherty|date=21 March 2002|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|publisher=RT\u00c9 Sport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215215325/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0321/162944-snooker/|archive-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> [[Ken Doherty]] played Lee in the second quarter-final. Lee achieved the match's top break of 90 as he drew the score at 2\u20132 and forced a re-spotted black after Doherty was out of position on the pink. Lee missed his target and Doherty took frame five before it went to 4\u20133 after Doherty incurred five fouls from being {{Cuegloss|snooker|snookered}} on the {{Cuegloss|green ball}} in the seventh. Lee took two of the following three frames to claim a 6\u20134 victory.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McHenry|first=Bruce|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84082345/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=d4c10af3|title=Doherty homes in on glory in Dublin|date=22 March 2002|work=[[The Scotsman]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=13|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe third quarter-final was played between Hendry and [[John Higgins]], the world number three.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hendon|first=David|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84118622/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=9afda954|title=Sport in brief: Snooker|date=23 March 2002|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=19 April 2020|url-status=live|page=19|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Breaks of 72, 131 and 96 gave Higgins a 3\u20131 lead before Hendry compiled a 64 run and a 137 {{Cuegloss|total clearance}} to tie at 3\u20133. Higgins increased his lead to 5\u20133 with breaks of 54, 67 and 43 until Hendry made it 5\u20134 with a break of 65. He took a 6\u20134 win after tactical play in frame ten.<ref name=110HendryKick>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05316.php|title=Hendry Sick Over Crucial Kick|last=Hendon|first=David|date=22 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030923040602/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05316.php|archive-date=23 September 2003|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Stevens defeated O'Sullivan 6\u20132 to claim the fourth semi-final spot. His victory saw him produce breaks of 68, 66 and 120 and accumulate 358 points without reply as O'Sullivan's best contributions were breaks of 103 and 88. At the post-match press conference, O'Sullivan gave monosyllabic answers to questions and stated the result was not the consequence of him fracturing his right hand in a game of [[association football]] the week before.<ref name=BBCStevens>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/1888725.stm|title=Stevens masters O'Sullivan|date=22 March 2002|publisher=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 February 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Semi-finals===\nBoth semi-finals were held as best-of-11 frames on 23&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=\"110Schedule\" /> Doherty and Ebdon played in the first match, which lasted more than four hours.<ref name=DohertyEbdonRTE>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0323/162987-dohertyk/|title=Doherty bows out at semi stage|last=Murray|first=Shane|date=23 March 2002|publisher=RT\u00c9 Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216083335/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0323/162987-dohertyk/|archive-date=16 February 2020|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> The match was tied at 3\u20133,<ref name=DohertyEbdonRTE/> as Ebdon made breaks of 104, 84 and 62 and missed the final red ball in frame seventh while trying to achieve a [[maximum break]].<ref name=WSDohertyEbdon>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=782&category=56|title=Irish Eyes Aren't Smiling As Ken Goes Out|date=23 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020614031640/http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=782&category=56|archive-date=14 June 2002|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> After the mid-session interval, Doherty accumulated a total of 73 points as he was unable to respond to the pressure of Ebdon who won 6\u20133.<ref name=WSDohertyEbdon /> Ebdon commented afterwards that the match was untidy and he could not make high breaks. He said he was happy to reach the final because the Irish Masters was one of his favourite competitions since he had won it in [[1995 Irish Masters|1995]].<ref name=110SF1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05319.php|title=Doherty Dumped Out In Dublin|last=Hendon|first=David|date=23 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030511091104/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05319.php|archive-date=11 May 2013|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Doherty said his technique was sub-par, and the match disappointed himself and the spectators: \"It was hard to get into it and when you\u2019re not playing well you lose control of the cue ball and make all sort of mistakes.\u201d<ref name=110SF1/>\n\n[[File:WSoS 2008 Moscow-32.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt= John Higgins looking at the camera |[[John Higgins]] ''(pictured in 2008)'', who won his second Irish Masters title]]\n\nThe other semi-final was contested by Higgins and Stevens. Stevens took a 3\u20130 lead before he had a {{Cuegloss|kick}} on the {{Cuegloss|brown ball}} and allowed Higgins to win five frames in succession that saw him produce a total clearance of 140 in frame eight, the highest break of the tournament. Stevens equalled the score at 5\u20135 to force a final frame; Higgins won it with a break of 42 for a 6\u20135 victory.<ref name=WSF2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=783&category=56|title=Higgins Builds On Lucky Break|date=24 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020614031618/http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=783&category=56|archive-date=14 June 2002|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Higgins said he was fortunate to have made the final because he noted that Stevens would have held a 4\u20130 lead had he not made an error early in the match: \"It was very unlucky but it was up to me to take advantage and I managed to do that, despite letting it slip at 5\u20133.\"<ref name=WSF2/>\n\n===Final===\n\nThe final between Ebdon and Higgins on 24&nbsp;March was contested over two sessions as a best-of-19 frames match.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=\"110Schedule\" /> Ebdon had won 8 of his 13 previous meetings against Higgins going into the match.<ref name=\"TimesFinal\">{{cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84168139/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=aec6dfb7|title=Higgins touches heights to leave Ebdon reeling; Snooker|date=25 March 2002|work=The Times|accessdate=16 February 2020|url-status=live|page=26|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The first session saw Higgins move into a 7\u20132 lead from breaks of 91, 109, 78 and two clearances of 55 and 62 to the brown ball. After the match resumed play, Higgins took the first frame of the evening session before Ebdon won frame eleven with a break of 64 to trail 3\u20138. Higgins then claimed the next two frames to win the game 10\u20133 and the tournament.<ref name=\"RTEFinal\">{{cite news|last=Murray|first=Shane|title=Higgins stuns Ebdon to win Irish Masters|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0324/163015-irishmasters1/|publisher=RT\u00c8 Sport|date=24 March 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216092507/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0324/163015-irishmasters1/|archive-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> It was the Higgins' second Irish Masters win; he won 9\u20134 against Hendry in the [[2000 Irish Masters|2000 tournament]].<ref name=\"RTEFinal\" /> Higgins won his fourth title of the season after the [[2001 Champions Cup|Champions Cup]], the [[2001 Scottish Masters|Scottish Masters]] and the [[2001 British Open|British Open]],<ref name=\"BEMFinal\">{{cite news|title=Snooker: Higgins happy from Dublin triumph|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84170638/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=7603ff88|work=[[Birmingham Mail|Birmingham Evening Mail]]|date=25 March 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020|page=56|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and the 24th of his career.<ref name=\"RTEFinal\" /> \n\nHiggins earned \u20ac100,000 for winning the competition and another \u20ac5,000 for making the highest break of 140 over Stevens in the semi-finals.<ref name=\"WSFinal\">{{cite web|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=784&category=56|title=Higgins Back To Winning Ways|date=24 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020820192612/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=784&category=56|archivedate=20 August 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> He said he was delighted to win the tournament for a second time,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/it-s-child-s-play-for-da-higgins-1.1055000|title=It's child's play for da Higgins|date=25 March 2002|work=The Irish Times|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216134608/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/it-s-child-s-play-for-da-higgins-1.1055000?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fsport%2Fit-s-child-s-play-for-da-higgins-1.1055000|archivedate=16 February 2020}}</ref> and said the victory would make him confident for the [[2002 World Snooker Championship|2002 World Championship]] because he had a poor form over the prior months: \"Winning there isn't easy when you're not sure of your game but this is a real boost for me'.\"<ref name=\"BEMFinal\" /> Ebdon said of his defeat: \"John is one of the finest match-players the game has ever seen and I was never going to beat him playing like that. I've got a very good record against him but it counts for nothing if you don't play well enough. It's a shame I couldn't make more of a match of it but I've beaten some good players this week so I can take the positives.\"<ref name=\"BPostFinal\">{{cite news|title=Snooker: Higgins rides his luck to victory|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84138971/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=4d87718d|work=[[Birmingham Post]]|date=25 March 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription|page=26}}</ref> He added: \"I was outclassed.\"<ref name=\"TimesFinal\" />\n\n==Main draw==\nPlayers in bold denote match winners.<ref name=SOrgEntry/><ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Masters|url=http://www.snookerscene.co.uk/page.php?id=25|publisher=Snooker Scene|accessdate=21 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124071613/http://www.snookerscene.co.uk/page.php?id=25|archivedate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n{{16TeamBracket-Compact-NoSeeds-Byes\n| RD1=Round 1<br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD2=Quarter-finals<br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD3=Semi-finals<br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD4=Final<br/>Best of 19 frames\n| RD1-seed03=5\n| RD1-team03={{Flagathlete|'''[[Stephen Hendry]]'''|SCO}} \n| RD1-score03='''6'''\n| RD1-seed04=12\n| RD1-team04={{Flagathlete|[[Fergal O'Brien]]|IRL}}\n| RD1-score04=2\n| RD1-seed07=6\n| RD1-team07={{Flagathlete|'''[[Matthew Stevens]]'''|WAL}} \n| RD1-score07='''6'''\n| RD1-seed08=11\n| RD1-team08={{Flagathlete|[[Jimmy White]]|ENG}} \n| RD1-score08=5\n| RD1-seed11=7\n| RD1-team11={{Flagathlete|'''[[Peter Ebdon]]'''|ENG}}\n| RD1-score11='''6'''\n| RD1-seed12=10\n| RD1-team12={{Flagathlete|[[Joe Swail]]|NIR}}\n| RD1-score12=2\n| RD1-seed15=8\n| RD1-team15={{Flagathlete|'''[[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]]'''|ENG}} \n| RD1-score15='''6'''\n| RD1-seed16=9\n| RD1-team16={{Flagathlete|[[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]]|ENG}} \n| RD1-score16=4\n| RD2-seed01=3\n| RD2-team01={{Flagicon|SCO}} '''[[John Higgins]]'''\n| RD2-score01='''6'''\n| RD2-seed02=5\n| RD2-team02={{Flagicon|SCO}} [[Stephen Hendry]]\n| RD2-score02=4\n| RD2-seed03=6\n| RD2-team03={{Flagicon|WAL}} '''[[Matthew Stevens]]'''\n| RD2-score03='''6'''\n| RD2-seed04=1\n| RD2-team04={{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n| RD2-score04=2\n| RD2-seed05=7\n| RD2-team05={{Flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Peter Ebdon]]'''\n| RD2-score05='''6'''\n| RD2-seed06=2\n| RD2-team06={{Flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]]\n| RD2-score06=4\n| RD2-seed07=4\n| RD2-team07={{Flagicon|IRL}} '''[[Ken Doherty]]'''\n| RD2-score07='''6'''\n| RD2-seed08=8\n| RD2-team08={{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]]\n| RD2-score08=4\n| RD3-seed01=3\n| RD3-team01={{Flagicon|SCO}} '''[[John Higgins]]'''\n| RD3-score01='''6'''\n| RD3-seed02=6\n| RD3-team02={{Flagicon|WAL}} [[Matthew Stevens]]\n| RD3-score02=5\n| RD3-seed03=7\n| RD3-team03={{Flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Peter Ebdon]]'''\n| RD3-score03='''6'''\n| RD3-seed04=4\n| RD3-team04={{Flagicon|IRL}} [[Ken Doherty]]\n| RD3-score04=3\n| RD4-seed01=3\n| RD4-team01={{Flagicon|SCO}} '''[[John Higgins]]'''\n| RD4-score01='''10'''\n| RD4-seed02=7\n| RD4-team02={{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Peter Ebdon]]\n| RD4-score02=3\n}}\n\n==Scoreline of the final==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| '''Final:''' Best of 19 frames.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><br />Citywest Hotel, [[Dublin]], Republic of Ireland, 24 March 2002.<ref name=\"WSFinal\"/>\n|-\n|  style=\"width:200px; text-align:right;\"|'''[[John Higgins]]'''<br/>{{SCO}}\n|  style=\"width:100px; text-align:center;\"| '''10'''\u20133\n| style=\"width:200px;\"|[[Peter Ebdon]] <br/>{{ENG}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"  style=\"text-align:center; font-size:100%;\"|''Afternoon'': '''91''' ('''91''')\u201339, '''61'''\u201314, 46\u2013'''71''', '''63'''\u20132, '''133'''\u20134 ('''109'''), 56 (56)\u2013'''66''' ('''66'''), '''69''' ('''69''')\u201362 (62), '''78''' ('''78''')\u20130, '''61''' ('''55''')\u201330<br/>''Evening'': '''87'''\u201318, 19\u2013'''94''', '''79''' ('''79''')\u20130, '''78'''\u201339\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''109'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Highest break\n| 79\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''1'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Century breaks\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''7'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 50+ breaks\n| 3\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Irish Masters}}\n{{Snooker season 2001/2002}}\n\n[[Category:2002 in snooker|Irish Masters]]\n[[Category:2002 in Irish sport|Irish Masters]]\n[[Category:March 2002 sports events in Europe|Irish Masters]]\n[[Category:Irish Masters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox Individual Snooker Tournament\n|tournament_name=Irish Masters\n|dates=19\u201324 March 2002\n|venue=Citywest Hotel\n|location=[[Saggart]], [[Dublin]]\n|country=Republic of Ireland\n|organisation=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]\n|format=Non-[[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]] event\n|Total prize fund=\u20ac251,000\n|winners_share=\u20ac100,000\n|highest_break={{flagathlete|[[John Higgins]]|SCO}} (140)\n|winner={{flagathlete|[[John Higgins]]|SCO}}\n|runner_up={{flagathlete|[[Peter Ebdon]]|ENG}}\n|score=10\u20133\n|previous=[[2001 Irish Masters|2001]]\n|next=[[2003 Irish Masters|2003]]\n}}\nThe '''2002 Irish Masters''' (known as the '''2002 Citywest Irish Masters''' for sponsorship reasons) was a professional invitational [[snooker]] tournament which was held at the Citywest Hotel in [[Saggart]], [[Dublin]], from 19&nbsp;to 24&nbsp;March. It was the 25th edition of the [[Irish Masters]] and the fourth and final [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA) invitational event of the [[2001\u201302 snooker season|2001\u201302 season]]. The tournament was co-sponsored by the Citywest hotel group and the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Department of Health and Children]] and broadcast by [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]. The competition followed the season's third invitational event, the [[2002 Masters (snooker)|2002 Masters]].\n\n[[John Higgins]], the world number three, won the competition, defeating the world number seven [[Peter Ebdon]] ten {{cuegloss|frame|frames}} to three (10\u20133) in the final. It was Higgins' second Irish Masters victory, his fourth in a tournament that season and the 24th of his career. In the semi-finals Higgins defeated [[Matthew Stevens]] 6\u20135 and Ebdon won 6\u20133 over [[Ken Doherty]]. Higgins produced the tournament's highest {{cuegloss|break}} of 140 in the eighth frame of his semi-final match against Stevens to earn \u20ac5,000 and a further \u20ac100,000 for winning the event. \n\n==Background==\nFounded in 1978 by the [[Benson & Hedges]] tobacco company as the [[Republic of Ireland]]'s major snooker event, the [[Irish Masters]] originated as a snooker [[Exhibition game|challenge match]] and became an elimination tournament.<ref name=\"Irish Masters\">{{cite web|last=Turner|first=Chris|title=Irish Masters|url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/irishmast.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216155735/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/irishmast.html|archivedate=16 February 2012|publisher=Chris Turner's Snooker Archive|accessdate=18 November 2010}}</ref> The 2002 competition was the 25th edition of the competition,<ref name=\"Preview\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/o-sullivan-leads-star-cast-1.1050966|title=O'Sullivan leads star cast|date=19 February 2002|work=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=19 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419190852/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/o-sullivan-leads-star-cast-1.1050966|archive-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> and the fourth and final [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] (WPBSA) invitational event of the [[2001\u201302 snooker season|2001\u201302 season]].<ref name=\"SOrgEntry\" /> It featured a 12-player main draw held at the Citywest Hotel in [[Saggart]], [[Dublin]], from&nbsp;19 to 24&nbsp;March,<ref name=\"Irish Masters\" /><ref name=SOrgEntry>{{cite web|title=Citywest Irish Masters 2002|url=http://www.snooker.org/Trn/0102/im2002_res.shtml|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=15 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020205531/http://www.snooker.org/TRN/0102/im2002_res.shtml|archive-date=20 October 2019}}</ref> and was co-sponsored by the hotel group [[Citywest]] and the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Department of Health and Children]].<ref name=\"Irish Masters\" /><ref name=\"Preview\">{{cite web|title=Ronnie Aims For Irish Repeat|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=688&category=56|publisher=World Snooker|date=19 March 2002|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021223144539/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=688&category=56|archivedate=23 December 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> It had a prize fund of \u20ac251,000,<ref name=\"PrizeMoney\">{{cite web|title=Prize Money Breakdown|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/money.asp|publisher=World Snooker|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020820192644/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/money.asp|archivedate=20 August 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the host broadcaster was [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA total of 12 players competed in the Irish Masters: the top eleven players in the [[Snooker world rankings 2001/2002|world rankings]],<ref name=\"Preview\" /> and a [[Wild card (sports)|wild card]] entry, the world number sixteen, [[Fergal O'Brien]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Murray|first=Shane|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0218/162198-snooker/|title=Irish Masters details announced|date=18 February 2002|access-date=15 February 2002|url-status=live|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215203250/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0218/162198-snooker/|archive-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Each of the 12 players were [[Seed (sports)|seeded]], with the first seed being [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]], the 2001 Irish Masters winner, and the reigning [[2001 UK Championship|UK]] and [[2001 World Snooker Championship|world champion]].<ref name=\"Preview\" /> [[Steve Davis]], the eight-time Irish Masters winner, missed the event for the first time since the [[1986 Irish Masters|1986 tournament]] because he fell to 21st in the world rankings and was not given a wild card.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yates|first=Phil|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A83999386/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=364d71aa|title=No place for Davis at the top table; Snooker|date=19 March 2002|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=43|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The number of maximum {{cuegloss|frame|frames}} played in a match increased from 11 in the first round, the quarter-finals and the semi-finals to the best-of-19 frames final on 24 March.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\">{{cite web|title=Citywest Irish Masters 2002|url=http://www.worldofsnooker.co.uk/invitational/irishmasters02.htm|publisher=World of Snooker|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020623132850/http://www.worldofsnooker.co.uk/invitational/irishmasters02.htm|archivedate=23 June 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Prize money===\nThe breakdown of prize money for the 2002 tournament is listed below.<ref name=\"PrizeMoney\" />\n{{col-begin}}\n* Winner: \u20ac100,000\n* Runner-up:  \u20ac38,000\n* Semi-final (\u00d72): \u20ac19,000\n* Quarter-final (\u00d74): \u20ac10,000\n* First-round (\u00d74):  \u20ac7,500\n* Highest break (\u00d71): \u20ac5,000\n* Total:  \u20ac251,000\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Tournament summary==\n===Round 1===\nThe first round of the tournament was held from 19&nbsp;to 20&nbsp;March as best-of-11 frame matches.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=110Schedule>{{cite web|title=Citywest Irish Masters|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/utils/displaypage.php?page=/snooker/cont/trn/sched/irishmastersoop02.php|publisher=110Sport|accessdate=15 February 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020421090902/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/php/utils/displaypage.php?page=%2Fsnooker%2Fcont%2Ftrn%2Fsched%2Firishmastersoop02.php|archivedate=21 April 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> World number eight [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] defeated the reigning Masters champion [[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]] 6\u20134 in their third meeting of the season.<ref name=LeeHunter110>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05301.php|title=Lee Foxes Hunter To End Dublin Drought|last=Hendon|first=David|date=19 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030523042858/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05301.php|archive-date=23 May 2003|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=LeeHunterIndy>{{Cite news|last=Francis|first=Allen|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84008154/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=413d3d68|title=Snooker: Lee to face familiar foe|date=20 March 2002|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=25|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The match was equalled at 3\u20133 and then 4\u20134 before Lee compiled {{Cuegloss|break|breaks}} of 72 and 88 to go through to the quarter-finals.<ref name=LeeHunterIndy/> Lee said he had worked to improve his technique and was pleased with it.<ref name=LeeHunter110/> World number seven [[Peter Ebdon]] won 6\u20132 against world championship semi-finalist [[Joe Swail]]. Ebdon compiled breaks of 120 and 81 to move clear of Swail and win the match\u2014this after Swail had missed a {{Cuegloss|red ball}} that would have allowed him to win the fifth frame. Both players agreed that Swail's error was the game's turning point.<ref name=WSSwailRed>{{Cite web|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=772&category=56|title=Crucial Miss Puts Swail In The Red|date=20 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020406093822/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=772&category=56|archive-date=6 April 2002|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Matthew Stevens]] won 6\u20135 over [[Jimmy White]], who made his 20th successive appearance in the Irish Masters.<ref name=BBCDay2>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/1884361.stm|title=Stevens and Hendry cruise|date=20 March 2002|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215203301/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/1884361.stm|archive-date=15 February 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Ahead 3\u20131, Stevens fell 4\u20133 behind White at the mid-session interval after he produced breaks of 106 and 102 and a {{Cuegloss|clearance}} of 65 to the {{Cuegloss|black ball}}.<ref name=StevensWhite110>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05306.php|title=Today Defeat, Tomorrow The World For Jimmy|last=Hendon|first=David|date=20 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020421054955/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05306.php|archive-date=15 April 2002|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> White missed a red to win the match while on a break of 62 and Stevens made a 58 clearance to the {{Cuegloss|pink ball}}. Stevens missed the black and White {{Cuegloss|pot|potted}} it to force a final frame,<ref name=StevensWhite110/> which Stevens won 75\u201314.<ref name=BBCDay2/> [[Stephen Hendry]], the seven-time world champion, took a 6\u20132 victory over O'Brien. Leading 2\u20131 with a break of 74, O'Brien was tied when Hendry produced a 112 break. Hendry then made breaks of 98 and 100 en route to his win as O'Brien accumulated 41 points in that time.<ref name=HendryHerald>{{Cite news|last=Price|first=Gerald|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84045249/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=63aa481c|title=Hendry's centuries are enough|date=21 March 2002|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=34|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Quarter-finals===\nThe four best-of-11 frame quarter-finals took place from 21&nbsp;to 22&nbsp;March with the first-round winners playing one of the top four seeds.<ref name=\"Irish Masters\" /><ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=\"110Schedule\" /> Ebdon was the first player through to the semi-finals when he defeated world number one [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 6\u20134. He took a 5\u20132 lead from breaks of 110, 77 and 113 along with a 93 clearance. Williams then reduced the deficit to 5\u20134 before he missed the black in the tenth frame and Ebdon won the match.<ref name=RTEEbdon>{{Cite news|last=Murray|first=Shane|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0321/162944-snooker/|title=Ebdon secures possible semi clash with Doherty|date=21 March 2002|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|publisher=RT\u00c9 Sport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215215325/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0321/162944-snooker/|archive-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> [[Ken Doherty]] played Lee in the second quarter-final. Lee achieved the match's top break of 90 as he drew the score at 2\u20132 and forced a re-spotted black after Doherty was out of position on the pink. Lee missed his target and Doherty took frame five before it went to 4\u20133 after Doherty incurred five fouls from being {{Cuegloss|snooker|snookered}} on the {{Cuegloss|green ball}} in the seventh. Lee took two of the following three frames to claim a 6\u20134 victory.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McHenry|first=Bruce|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84082345/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=d4c10af3|title=Doherty homes in on glory in Dublin|date=22 March 2002|work=[[The Scotsman]]|access-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live|page=13|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe third quarter-final was played between Hendry and [[John Higgins]], the world number three.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hendon|first=David|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84118622/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=9afda954|title=Sport in brief: Snooker|date=23 March 2002|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=19 April 2020|url-status=live|page=19|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Breaks of 72, 131 and 96 gave Higgins a 3\u20131 lead before Hendry compiled a 64 run and a 137 {{Cuegloss|total clearance}} to tie at 3\u20133. Higgins increased his lead to 5\u20133 with breaks of 54, 67 and 43 until Hendry made it 5\u20134 with a break of 65. He took a 6\u20134 win after tactical play in frame ten.<ref name=110HendryKick>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05316.php|title=Hendry Sick Over Crucial Kick|last=Hendon|first=David|date=22 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030923040602/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05316.php|archive-date=23 September 2003|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Stevens defeated O'Sullivan 6\u20132 to claim the fourth semi-final spot. His victory saw him produce breaks of 68, 66 and 120 and accumulate 358 points without reply as O'Sullivan's best contributions were breaks of 103 and 88. At the post-match press conference, O'Sullivan gave monosyllabic answers to questions and stated the result was not the consequence of him fracturing his right hand in a game of [[association football]] the week before.<ref name=BBCStevens>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/1888725.stm|title=Stevens masters O'Sullivan|date=22 March 2002|publisher=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 February 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Semi-finals===\nBoth semi-finals were held as best-of-11 frames on 23&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=\"110Schedule\" /> Doherty and Ebdon played in the first match, which lasted more than four hours.<ref name=DohertyEbdonRTE>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0323/162987-dohertyk/|title=Doherty bows out at semi stage|last=Murray|first=Shane|date=23 March 2002|publisher=RT\u00c9 Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216083335/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0323/162987-dohertyk/|archive-date=16 February 2020|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> The match was tied at 3\u20133,<ref name=DohertyEbdonRTE/> as Ebdon made breaks of 104, 84 and 62 and missed the final red ball in frame seventh while trying to achieve a [[maximum break]].<ref name=WSDohertyEbdon>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=782&category=56|title=Irish Eyes Aren't Smiling As Ken Goes Out|date=23 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020614031640/http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=782&category=56|archive-date=14 June 2002|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> After the mid-session interval, Doherty accumulated a total of 73 points as he was unable to respond to the pressure of Ebdon who won 6\u20133.<ref name=WSDohertyEbdon /> Ebdon commented afterwards that the match was untidy and he could not make high breaks. He said he was happy to reach the final because the Irish Masters was one of his favourite competitions since he had won it in [[1995 Irish Masters|1995]].<ref name=110SF1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05319.php|title=Doherty Dumped Out In Dublin|last=Hendon|first=David|date=23 March 2002|publisher=110Sport|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030511091104/http://www.110sport.com/snooker/cont/art/na05319.php|archive-date=11 May 2013|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Doherty said his technique was sub-par, and the match disappointed himself and the spectators: \"It was hard to get into it and when you\u2019re not playing well you lose control of the cue ball and make all sort of mistakes.\u201d<ref name=110SF1/>\n\n[[File:WSoS 2008 Moscow-32.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt= John Higgins looking at the camera |[[John Higgins]] ''(pictured in 2008)'', who won his second Irish Masters title]]\n\nThe other semi-final was contested by Higgins and Stevens. Stevens took a 3\u20130 lead before he had a {{Cuegloss|kick}} on the {{Cuegloss|brown ball}} and allowed Higgins to win five frames in succession that saw him produce a total clearance of 140 in frame eight, the highest break of the tournament. Stevens equalled the score at 5\u20135 to force a final frame; Higgins won it with a break of 42 for a 6\u20135 victory.<ref name=WSF2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=783&category=56|title=Higgins Builds On Lucky Break|date=24 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020614031618/http://www.worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=783&category=56|archive-date=14 June 2002|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Higgins said he was fortunate to have made the final because he noted that Stevens would have held a 4\u20130 lead had he not made an error early in the match: \"It was very unlucky but it was up to me to take advantage and I managed to do that, despite letting it slip at 5\u20133.\"<ref name=WSF2/>\n\n===Final===\n\nThe final between Ebdon and Higgins on 24&nbsp;March was contested over two sessions as a best-of-19 frames match.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref name=\"110Schedule\" /> Ebdon had won 8 of his 13 previous meetings against Higgins going into the match.<ref name=\"TimesFinal\">{{cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84168139/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=aec6dfb7|title=Higgins touches heights to leave Ebdon reeling; Snooker|date=25 March 2002|work=The Times|accessdate=16 February 2020|url-status=live|page=26|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The first session saw Higgins move into a 7\u20132 lead from breaks of 91, 109, 78 and two clearances of 55 and 62 to the brown ball. After the match resumed play, Higgins took the first frame of the evening session before Ebdon won frame eleven with a break of 64 to trail 3\u20138. Higgins then claimed the next two frames to win the game 10\u20133 and the tournament.<ref name=\"RTEFinal\">{{cite news|last=Murray|first=Shane|title=Higgins stuns Ebdon to win Irish Masters|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0324/163015-irishmasters1/|publisher=RT\u00c8 Sport|date=24 March 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216092507/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2002/0324/163015-irishmasters1/|archive-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> It was the Higgins' second Irish Masters win; he won 9\u20134 against Hendry in the [[2000 Irish Masters|2000 tournament]].<ref name=\"RTEFinal\" /> Higgins won his fourth title of the season after the [[2001 Champions Cup|Champions Cup]], the [[2001 Scottish Masters|Scottish Masters]] and the [[2001 British Open|British Open]],<ref name=\"BEMFinal\">{{cite news|title=Snooker: Higgins happy from Dublin triumph|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84170638/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=7603ff88|work=[[Birmingham Mail|Birmingham Evening Mail]]|date=25 March 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020|page=56|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and the 24th of his career.<ref name=\"RTEFinal\" /> \n\nHiggins earned \u20ac100,000 for winning the competition and another \u20ac5,000 for making the highest break of 140 over Stevens in the semi-finals.<ref name=\"WSFinal\">{{cite web|url=http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=784&category=56|title=Higgins Back To Winning Ways|date=24 March 2002|publisher=World Snooker|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020820192612/http://worldsnooker.com/snooker_media_centre/irish_masters2002/articleshow.asp?articleID=784&category=56|archivedate=20 August 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> He said he was delighted to win the tournament for a second time,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/it-s-child-s-play-for-da-higgins-1.1055000|title=It's child's play for da Higgins|date=25 March 2002|work=The Irish Times|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216134608/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/it-s-child-s-play-for-da-higgins-1.1055000?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fsport%2Fit-s-child-s-play-for-da-higgins-1.1055000|archivedate=16 February 2020}}</ref> and said the victory would make him confident for the [[2002 World Snooker Championship|2002 World Championship]] because he had a poor form over the prior months: \"Winning there isn't easy when you're not sure of your game but this is a real boost for me'.\"<ref name=\"BEMFinal\" /> Ebdon said of his defeat: \"John is one of the finest match-players the game has ever seen and I was never going to beat him playing like that. I've got a very good record against him but it counts for nothing if you don't play well enough. It's a shame I couldn't make more of a match of it but I've beaten some good players this week so I can take the positives.\"<ref name=\"BPostFinal\">{{cite news|title=Snooker: Higgins rides his luck to victory|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A84138971/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=4d87718d|work=[[Birmingham Post]]|date=25 March 2002|accessdate=16 February 2020|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription|page=26}}</ref> He added: \"I was outclassed.\"<ref name=\"TimesFinal\" />\n\n==Main draw==\nPlayers in bold denote match winners.<ref name=SOrgEntry/><ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Masters|url=http://www.snookerscene.co.uk/page.php?id=25|publisher=Snooker Scene|accessdate=21 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124071613/http://www.snookerscene.co.uk/page.php?id=25|archivedate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n{{16TeamBracket-Compact-NoSeeds-Byes\n| RD1=Round 1<br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD2=Quarter-finals<br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD3=Semi-finals<br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD4=Final<br/>Best of 19 frames\n| RD1-team03={{Flagathlete|'''[[Stephen Hendry]]'''|SCO}} \n| RD1-score03='''6'''\n| RD1-team04={{Flagathlete|[[Fergal O'Brien]]|IRL}}\n| RD1-score04=2\n| RD1-team07={{Flagathlete|'''[[Matthew Stevens]]'''|WAL}} \n| RD1-score07='''6'''\n| RD1-team08={{Flagathlete|[[Jimmy White]]|ENG}} \n| RD1-score08=5\n| RD1-team11={{Flagathlete|'''[[Peter Ebdon]]'''|ENG}}\n| RD1-score11='''6'''\n| RD1-team12={{Flagathlete|[[Joe Swail]]|NIR}}\n| RD1-score12=2\n| RD1-team15={{Flagathlete|'''[[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]]'''|ENG}} \n| RD1-score15='''6'''\n| RD1-team16={{Flagathlete|[[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]]|ENG}} \n| RD1-score16=4\n| RD2-team01={{Flagicon|SCO}} '''[[John Higgins]]'''\n| RD2-score01='''6'''\n| RD2-team02={{Flagicon|SCO}} [[Stephen Hendry]]\n| RD2-score02=4\n| RD2-team03={{Flagicon|WAL}} '''[[Matthew Stevens]]'''\n| RD2-score03='''6'''\n| RD2-team04={{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n| RD2-score04=2\n| RD2-team05={{Flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Peter Ebdon]]'''\n| RD2-score05='''6'''\n| RD2-team06={{Flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]]\n| RD2-score06=4\n| RD2-team07={{Flagicon|IRL}} '''[[Ken Doherty]]'''\n| RD2-score07='''6'''\n| RD2-team08={{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]]\n| RD2-score08=4\n| RD3-team01={{Flagicon|SCO}} '''[[John Higgins]]'''\n| RD3-score01='''6'''\n| RD3-team02={{Flagicon|WAL}} [[Matthew Stevens]]\n| RD3-score02=5\n| RD3-team03={{Flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Peter Ebdon]]'''\n| RD3-score03='''6'''\n| RD3-team04={{Flagicon|IRL}} [[Ken Doherty]]\n| RD3-score04=3\n| RD4-team01={{Flagicon|SCO}} '''[[John Higgins]]'''\n| RD4-score01='''10'''\n| RD4-team02={{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Peter Ebdon]]\n| RD4-score02=3\n}}\n\n==Scoreline of the final==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| '''Final:''' Best of 19 frames.<ref name=\"WoSFormat\" /><br />Citywest Hotel, [[Dublin]], Republic of Ireland, 24 March 2002.<ref name=\"WSFinal\"/>\n|-\n|  style=\"width:200px; text-align:right;\"|'''[[John Higgins]]'''<br/>{{SCO}}\n|  style=\"width:100px; text-align:center;\"| '''10'''\u20133\n| style=\"width:200px;\"|[[Peter Ebdon]] <br/>{{ENG}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"  style=\"text-align:center; font-size:100%;\"|''Afternoon'': '''91''' ('''91''')\u201339, '''61'''\u201314, 46\u2013'''71''', '''63'''\u20132, '''133'''\u20134 ('''109'''), 56 (56)\u2013'''66''' ('''66'''), '''69''' ('''69''')\u201362 (62), '''78''' ('''78''')\u20130, '''61''' ('''55''')\u201330<br/>''Evening'': '''87'''\u201318, 19\u2013'''94''', '''79''' ('''79''')\u20130, '''78'''\u201339\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''109'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Highest break\n| 79\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''1'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Century breaks\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''7'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 50+ breaks\n| 3\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Irish Masters}}\n{{Snooker season 2001/2002}}\n\n[[Category:2002 in snooker|Irish Masters]]\n[[Category:2002 in Irish sport|Irish Masters]]\n[[Category:March 2002 sports events in Europe|Irish Masters]]\n[[Category:Irish Masters]]\n", "name_user": "MWright96", "label": "safe", "comment": "GA edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2002_Irish_Masters"}
{"title_page": "Athletics at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 400 metres hurdles", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Men's 400 metres hurdles\n|games = 1980 Summer\n|venue = [[Lenin Stadium (Moscow)|Lenin Stadium]]\n|dates = 25\u201326 July\n|nations = 20\n|competitors = 23\n|win_value = 48.70\n|longnames = yes\n|gold = [[Volker Beck (athlete)|Volker Beck]]\n|goldNOC = GDR\n|silver = [[Vasyl Arkhypenko]]\n|silverNOC = URS\n|bronze = [[Gary Oakes]]\n|bronzeNOC = GBR\n|prev = [[Athletics at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 400 metres hurdles|1976]]\n|next = [[Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 400 metres hurdles|1984]]\n}}\n{{AthleticsAt1980SummerOlympics}}\nThe '''Men's 400 metres Hurdles''' at the [[Athletics at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]] had an entry list of 23 competitors, with three qualifying heats (23 runners), two semi-finals (16) before the final (8) took place on Saturday July 26, 1980.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1980/ATH/mens-400-metres-hurdles.html |title=Athletics at the 1980 Moscow Summer Games: Men's 400 metres Hurdles |accessdate=5 October 2017 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Final==\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!RANK\n!style=\"width: 20em\"|FINAL\n!style=\"width: 5em\"|TIME\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[Image:Med 1.png]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Volker Beck (athlete)|Volker Beck]]|GDR|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''48.70'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[Image:Med 2.png]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vasyl Arkhypenko]]|URS|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''48.86'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[Image:Med 3.png]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Gary Oakes]]|GBR|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''49.11'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|4.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Nikolay Vasilyev (hurdler)|Nikolay Vasilyev]]|URS|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''49.34'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|5.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Rok Kopitar]]|YUG|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''49.67'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|6.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Horia Toboc]]|ROU|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''49.84'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|7.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Franz Meier]]|SUI|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''50.00  '''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|8.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Yanko Bratanov]]|BUL|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''56.35 '''\n|}\n\n==Semi finals==\n*Held on Friday 1980-07-25\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!RANK\n!style=\"width: 20em\"|HEAT 1\n!style=\"width: 5em\"|TIME\n|- style=\"background:#aaffaa;\"\n|align=\"center\"|1.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Volker Beck (athlete)|Volker Beck]]|GDR|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''50.36'''\n|- style=\"background:#aaffaa;\"\n|align=\"center\"|2.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Rok Kopitar]]|YUG|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''50.55'''\n|- style=\"background:#aaffaa;\"\n|align=\"center\"|3.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Horia Toboc]]|ROU|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''50.58'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|4.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Harry Schulting]]|NED|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''50.61'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|5.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Aleksandr Kharlov]]|URS|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''50.64'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|6.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[J\u00f3zsef Szalai]]|HUN|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''51.06  '''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|7.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Ant\u00f4nio Dias Ferreira]]|BRA|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''52.31  '''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|&mdash;\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Christer Gullstrand]]|SWE|1980 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''DNS '''\n|}\n<br />\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!RANK\n!style=\"width: 20em\"|HEAT 2\n!style=\"width: 5em\"|TIME\n|- style=\"background:#aaffaa;\"